### Part 3: Research & Philosophical Perspectives

#### 5. [When the Tower Crumbles: Losing the End-to-End Language with the Tower of AI](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-t2trg-when-the-tower-crumbles-losing-the-end-to-end-language-with-the-tower-of-ai-00)
* **Presenter**: Tobias Fiebig
* **Summary**: Tobias offered a highly skeptical, cautionary perspective on using AI to manage M2M communication. He argued that computer systems are already too complex for single individuals to understand. Adding AI to bridge incompatible vendor specifications introduces an unsustainable layer of abstraction. By outsourcing M2M interoperability to AI, human engineers will gradually "lose the language" required to program and debug these systems. If the AI "tower" crumbles (e.g., due to vendor bankruptcy, supply chain failures, or data center outages), humans will be left unable to maintain critical infrastructure.
* **Discussion**:
  * Dirk Kutscher and Esko Dijk pointed out that computer science relies fundamentally on abstractions, and complexity is an inevitable evolutionary trait. Christian Amsüss added that the goal must be finding the *right* abstractions that truly simplify the domain.
  * Carsten Bormann compared the shift to compiler technologies (losing assembly language fluency) but emphasized a key difference: compilers are backed by decades of rigorous science and testing frameworks. AI tools lack similar predictability, which is dangerous when they actuate physical hardware (the "hardware-in-the-loop" problem).
  * Niklas Winsth and Matthias Kovatsch noted that AI could assist with tedious tasks that humans cannot or do not want to do (such as helping laypeople integrate new smart home devices) and could help generate intermediate system documentation.
  * Tobias Fiebig concluded by arguing that the core issue is not technical, but rather a lack of business incentives for vendors to adopt existing open standards. He cautioned that using AI to patch bad vendor implementations bypasses the real problem and introduces hidden environmental and systemic costs.

